title: As it burns down, more wick is exposed, producing a larger and smokier flame, unless you periodically snip the wick. The fuss-saving innovation, which didn’t occur to anyone until 1825, is to braid the fibers of the wick as a flattened strip, so that it naturally curls over and the excess is consumed by the flame.
pid: 78f21191-5bb8-4960-8b5a-1d3452d223af
